1 "37-3-305. Qualifications for licensure. (1) Except as provided in subsection (2), the board shall
2 grant a physician's license to practice medicine in this state to an applicant who:
3 (a) is of good moral character as determined by the board;
4 (b) is a graduate of an approved medical school as defined in 37-3-102;
5 (c) has completed an approved residency program or, for an applicant who graduated from
6 medical school prior to 2000, has had experience or training that the board has determined is at least the
7 equivalent of an approved residency program;
8 (c) possesses one or more of the qualifications:
9 (i) has completed PGY-1 of an approved residency program, provided the individual remains
10 enrolled and in good standing throughout the residency program;
11 (ii) has completed an approved residency program; or
12 (iii) for an applicant who graduated from medical school prior to 2000, has experience or training
13 that the board determines is at least the equivalent of an approved residency program;
14 (d) has passed all of the steps of the United States medical licensing examination, the federation
15 of state medical boards' federation licensing examination, or an examination offered by any of the following
16 entities:
17 (i) the national board of medical examiners or its successors;
18 (ii) the national board of osteopathic medical examiners or its successors;
19 (iii) the medical council of Canada or its successors if the applicant is a graduate of a Canadian
20 medical school approved by the medical council of Canada or its successors; or
21 (iv) the educational commission for foreign medical graduates or its successors if the applicant is a
22 graduate of a foreign medical school outside of the United States and Canada;
23 (e) has submitted a completed application with the required nonrefundable fee; and
24 (f) is able to communicate in the English language as determined by the board.
25 (2) The board may authorize the department to issue the license subject to terms of probation or
26 other conditions or limitations set by the board or may refuse a license if the applicant has committed
27 unprofessional conduct or is otherwise unqualified.
